%I A397182 #31 Jul 04 2026 23:06:29
%S A397182 1,3,13,30
%N A397182 a(n) = maximum number of regions the plane can be divided into by drawing n constrained long-legged A's.
%C A397182 A constrained long-legged A is a planar graph consisting of two rays R and S (the arms) that emanate from a common point A (the tip), separated by an angle theta, two points B on R and C on S, with |AB| = |AC|, and the line segment BC (the crossbar).
%C A397182 More simply, a constrained long-legged A is a standard upper-case English letter A with both legs extended to infinity.
%C A397182 When we draw n A's the parameters A,B,C,R,S,theta may be different for each letter. Note that the full two-dimensional affine group acts transitively on the set of A's.
%C A397182 It is known that 54 <= a(4) <= 55, 85 <= a(5) <= 87, ... (see Table 6 of the "Cutting a pancake ..." paper for further bounds).
%H A397182 David O. H. Cutler, <a href="/A397182/a397182.png">Illustration for a(2) = 13</a>. [Fig. 33 from the "Cutting a pancake..." paper. One A has a purple tip, the other a brown tip. One of the intersection points between the two copis of the A is not shown: it occurs a long way below the bottom of the picture.]
%H A397182 David O. H. Cutler, <a href="/A397182/a397182.jpg">Illustration (a) for a(3) = 30</a>. [Fig. 34 from the "Cutting a pancake..." paper.
%H A397182 David O. H. Cutler, <a href="/A397182/a397182_1.jpg">Illustration (b) for a(3) = 30, showing an enlargement of the portion of the figure where the three crossbars come together</a>. [Fig. 35 from the "Cutting a pancake..." paper.
%H A397182 David O. H. Cutler, Jonas Karlsson, and Neil J. A. Sloane, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.15864">Cutting a Pancake with an Exotic Knife</a>, arXiv:2511.15864[math.CO], v3, April 19 2026.
